Data Acquisition (Step #1):

This week’s assignment will consist of two parts. First for Part #1, a series of SQL queries that you run on datasets that are either currently in your CARTO account; or a dataset(s) that you newly upload. As a default, you could utilize the Class 3 Lecture Demo Data.

The dataset for Part #2 is Airbnb archived data for unique global cities available HERE. To access, find the city that you are interested in working with in Part #2, and download its listings.csv instance. That dataset can then be loaded to CARTO as a .csv. The latitude and longitude columns in the dataset will be read by CARTO as geographic coordinates and stored as the_geom for mapping purposes. Conduct your SQL queries on the dataset now loaded to CARTO.

Part I SQL Queries (Step #2):

In this first assignment component, conduct 5 unique SQL query statements, one of which will be a non-spatial query (for instance a COUNT query).

Create a text document listing out your 5 SQL queries, making sure to separate each one for each access/viewing. Provide a screengrab of each successful result within the SQL and Map interface:

SQL + Map Interface

Part II SQL Queries (Step #3):

Using SQL and data from Inside Airbnb for the city of your choice answer the following 4 questions:

  1. How many Airbnb listings are there in the city you chose?
  2. How many listings are there in each neighborhood?
  3. What is the average price for an listing?
  4. Make a map where you filter the listings somehow (for example, showing listings with “beautiful” in their name).

  • For query #1, this can be accomplished by the non-spatial COUNT operator.

  • For query #2, utilize Count in groups from the SQL Cheatsheet.

  • For query #3 above, average is a similar EDA statistic to count; utilize w3schools overview to understand the syntax of both.

  • For query #4 above, finding a subset string/text within a larger string/text can be accomplished with the ILIKE operator as described in this overview. A description of the ILIKE operator is also available at end of SQL Cheatsheet.

Like Part #1, Create a text document listing out your 4 SQL queries, making sure to separate each one for each access/viewing. Provide a screengrab of each successful result within the SQL and Map interface.

Assignment 3 deliverable - SQL Queries (Step #4):

  • Once your SQL query process is complete for both part #1 and part #2 above, upload your final write-up with screengrabs to CANVAS for assignment 3 as as .pdf document.
